# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for this Next.js 16.1.6 project using the App Router.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version 2.0.0 using npm
- Package added to dependencies in package.json

### 2. Root Layout Update (src/app/layout.tsx)
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next";`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the `<body>` tag, placed after `{children}`
- Preserved all existing code structure and formatting

## Implementation Details

Since this is a Next.js 16.1.6 project with App Router (app directory structure), I used the recommended approach:
- Imported from `@vercel/speed-insights/next` (not the /react version)
- Placed the component in the root layout without any props (automatic route detection)
- No 'use client' directive needed as the component handles this internally

## Files Modified
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
- `package-lock.json` - Updated with new dependency tree
- `src/app/layout.tsx` - Added SpeedInsights component

## Verification

### Linting
- Ran ESLint on layout.tsx - no errors or warnings introduced
- Pre-existing lint errors in other files remain unchanged

### Build Testing
- Build process was tested but failed due to pre-existing issue with missing Supabase environment variables
- This is unrelated to the Speed Insights implementation
- The Speed Insights code itself is valid and will work once environment variables are configured

## Notes
- The SpeedInsights component will automatically track page transitions and performance metrics
- Data will be sent to Vercel when deployed on the Vercel platform
- No additional configuration is required for basic functionality
- The component is lightweight and won't affect page performance
